    <section id="resources">
        <h2>Resources</h2>
        <p>Food waste management is a critical aspect of sustainable living and environmental conservation. It involves the reduction, recovery, and recycling of discarded food to minimize its negative impact on the environment. Globally, about one-third of all food produced for human consumption is lost or wasted each year, contributing to significant economic, social, and environmental challenges.

The primary goals of food waste management are to decrease the environmental footprint associated with food disposal, alleviate the strain on landfills, and address the ethical concerns of hunger and resource scarcity. Strategies for effective management include promoting awareness about responsible consumption, encouraging proper storage and meal planning, and fostering collaborations between stakeholders across the food supply chain.

By implementing food waste management practices, individuals, businesses, and communities can contribute to a more sustainable future. These efforts not only conserve valuable resources but also reduce greenhouse gas emissions generated by decomposing organic waste in landfills. Overall, food waste management is a crucial component of the broader initiative to create a more environmentally conscious and resource-efficient society.</p>
